Rating: 4
I've made this several times as a creme brulee. I highly recommend using Meyer lemons; their mild lemon flavor complements the creaminess of the filling without overwhelming it. This recipe is worth getting a kitchen blowtorch for -- using a broiler will heat up the whole tart instead of just carmelizing the topping. I think that the finely grated lemon peel detracts from the smooth texture you usually expect in a creme brulee, so here's what I did: peel the Meyer lemons in long strips, then add them to the cream, heat gently, and allow the peel to steep in the cream for a while. Strain them out when adding the cream to the recipe, and strain the entire mixture again when pouring in the pan -- this will keep out lumps of egg that may curdle while cooking. Also, I bake in a water bath at about 340 degrees so that egg doesn't cook too quickly. The last time I added raspberries. Beautiful and delicious!!!

